		<title>In an Emoji History of Art, ND Stevenson Playfully Recreates Iconic Paintings</title>
		<link>https://www.sawberries.com/2024/05/02/emoji-art-history/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[ross]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 02 May 2024 21:01:20 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[art]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[art history]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[digital]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[humor]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[ND Stevenson]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.sawberries.com/2024/05/02/emoji-art-history/</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Gustav Klimt, “The Kiss.” All images © ND Stevenson More than 100 years after it was first exhibited, art historians still debate whether Marcel Duchamp’s “Fountain,” submitted to the 1917 Armory Show in New York, was a wry joke or sly commentary on modern art—or both. That’s because the sculpture, a urinal the artist signed [&#8230;]]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>
<div id="attachment_246360" style="width: 1090px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246360" class="wp-image-246360 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-8.jpeg" alt="an emoji recreation of two people embracing above flowers" width="1080" height="1920" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-8.jpeg 1080w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-8-640x1138.jpeg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-8-960x1707.jpeg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-8-864x1536.jpeg 864w" sizes="(max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246360" class="wp-caption-text">Gustav Klimt, “The Kiss.” All images © ND Stevenson</p>
</div>
<p>More than 100 years after it was first exhibited, art historians still debate whether <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcel_Duchamp" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Marcel Duchamp</a>’s “Fountain,” submitted to the 1917 Armory Show in New York, was a wry joke or sly commentary on modern art—or both. That’s because the sculpture, a urinal the artist signed “R. Mutt,” was just a standard piece of plumbing. But Duchamp is also known to have coined the term “<a href="https://www.tate.org.uk/art/art-terms/r/readymade" target="_blank" rel="noopener">readymade</a>,” in which he displayed objects like bicycle wheels or snow shovels as artworks unto themselves, posing the fundamental question that still thrills theorists: “But is it art?”</p>
<p>If Duchamp were around today to know what an emoji was, he’d probably love comic artist <a href="https://www.imfineimfine.com/archive" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ND Stevenson</a>’s take on “Fountain,” composed of a slew of what we might consider 21st-century digital readymades. A few years ago, the artist figured out that he could add countless icons to the standard Instagram stories template, resizing and rearranging them to create original compositions.</p>
<p>Starting with a basic background image, Stevenson adds numerous elements, like a fork standing in for a pitchfork in Grant Wood’s “American Gothic” or an upside-down red exclamation point in place of a necktie in René Magritte’s “The Son of Man.” For Johannes Vermeer’s “Girl with a Pearl Earring,” a bowl and a cloud provide the basis of the subject’s famous blue-and-white head wrap; a toilet stands in for Duchamp’s urinal; and numerous flowers, evil eyes, books, cheese, and urns make up the patterns of Klimt’s embracing figures in “The Kiss.”</p>
<p>It’s worth diving into <a href="https://www.imfineimfine.com/p/bonus-emoji-painting-gallery" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Stevenson’s post</a> for more emoji recreations.</p>
<p> </p>
<div id="attachment_246362" style="width: 1930px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246362" class="wp-image-246362 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-2.jpg" alt='left: two emoji people holding a fork. right" a woman with a blue bowl and cloud hat with a turkey gown' width="1920" height="1689" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-2.jpg 1920w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-2-640x563.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-2-960x845.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-2-1536x1351.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246362" class="wp-caption-text">Left: Grant Wood, “American Gothic.” Right: Johannes Vermeer, “Girl with a Pearl Earring”</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246366" style="width: 1090px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246366" class="wp-image-246366 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-6.jpeg" alt="an emoji man with a green apple over his face" width="1080" height="1920" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-6.jpeg 1080w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-6-640x1138.jpeg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-6-960x1707.jpeg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-6-864x1536.jpeg 864w" sizes="(max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246366" class="wp-caption-text">René Magritte, “The Son of Man”</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246364" style="width: 1930px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246364" class="wp-image-246364 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-4.jpg" alt="left: a man with a bleeding art grasps at a pen, ink, and paper. right: a toilet with r mutt 1917 written on it" width="1920" height="1689" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-4.jpg 1920w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-4-640x563.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-4-960x845.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-4-1536x1351.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246364" class="wp-caption-text">Left: Jacques-Louis David, “The Death of Marat.” Right: Marcel Duchamp, “Fountain”</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246365" style="width: 1466px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246365" class="wp-image-246365 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-5.jpeg" alt="emoji people and animals visit a lush lake" width="1456" height="819" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-5.jpeg 1456w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-5-640x360.jpeg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-5-960x540.jpeg 960w" sizes="(max-width: 1456px) 100vw, 1456px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246365" class="wp-caption-text">Georges Seurat, “A Sunday Afternoon on the Island of La Grande Jatte”</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246363" style="width: 1930px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246363" class="wp-image-246363 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-3.jpg" alt="left: people sit at a counter with coffee. right: four clocks appear among a shifting landscape" width="1920" height="1689" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-3.jpg 1920w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-3-640x563.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-3-960x845.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-3-1536x1351.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246363" class="wp-caption-text">Left: Edward Hopper, “Nighthawks.” Right: Salvador Dalí, “The Persistence of Memory”</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246361" style="width: 1090px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246361" class="wp-image-246361 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-7.jpeg" alt="the dancer emoji appears to swing amid a lush landscape with a soccer player, two baby angles, and a man in the foreground" width="1080" height="1920" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-7.jpeg 1080w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-7-640x1138.jpeg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-7-960x1707.jpeg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-7-864x1536.jpeg 864w" sizes="(max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246361" class="wp-caption-text">Jean-Honoré Fragonard, “The Swing”</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246367" style="width: 1930px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246367" class="wp-image-246367 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-1.jpg" alt="left: a nude man reaches his hand toward santa in the sky with several baby angels. right: a man with gray hair holding a steak and legs" width="1920" height="1689" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-1.jpg 1920w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-1-640x563.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-1-960x845.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/emojis-1-1536x1351.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246367" class="wp-caption-text">Left: Michelangelo, “The Creation of Adam” detail of the Sistine Chapel ceiling. Right: Francisco Goya, “Saturn Devouring His Son”</p>
</div>
